<HEADLINE>
<P>
DEATH PENALTY AND ABORTION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In response to Conrad's cartoon regarding the "supposed" inconsistency of an 
individual who is both pro-life and pro-capital punishment (Jan. 26), as one 
such individual, it seems apparent to me that the entire debate surrounds one 
single issue -- responsibility. 
</P>
<P>
An individual who is convicted of killing another human being and is sentenced 
to death must accept the consequences of his behavior. He made the decision 
before committing the crime and must not be allowed to shirk all responsibility 
for his actions. 
</P>
<P>
In a similar way, before a man and a woman engage in sexual intercourse they 
know there is a chance that the woman might become impregnated. Yet abortion is 
so often used as a way of avoiding responsibility. 
</P>
<P>
Yes, there is a major difference -- an individual who commits murder had a 
choice, babies in the womb have none. They should be given the right to choose 
and nobody has the right to decide for them. 
</P>
<P>
BRETT BARBRE 
</P>
<P>
Yorba Linda 
</P>
</TEXT>
