<HEADLINE>
<P>
NISSAN HOLDS LEAD AS FOG HALTS DAYTONA RACE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By AP 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A heavy shroud of fog rolled in off the Atlantic Ocean early Sunday morning, 
forcing IMSA officials to red-flag the Daytona 24 Hours Camel GT sports car 
race to a temporary halt after 10 hours 11 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
The stoppage came at 1:50 a.m. EST with Geoff Brabham, the defending Camel GT 
champion, leading in a Nissan GTP by two laps. 
</P>
<P>
The race clock continued during the red flag period, with the event still 
scheduled to conclude at 3:38 p.m. EST Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
Brabham, an Australian-born driver taking part in his first 24-hour event and 
driving at night for the first time in a race, drove the Nissan into the lead 
at 11:40 p.m. EST. 
</P>
<P>
He built a 90-second lead over the Jaguar of Jan Lammers, Davy Jones and Raul 
Boesel during the next hour, but made a scheduled pit stop at 12:40 a.m. 
</P>
<P>
Jones drove past in the Jaguar, retaking the lead that the car, last year's 
winner, had held several times earlier. But, one lap later, he pulled into the 
pits with an engine problem. 
</P>
<P>
The Nissan, shared by Chip Robinson and Arie Luyendyk of the Netherlands, moved 
back into the lead at the end of the 289th lap on the 3.56-mile Daytona 
International Speedway road circuit. 
</P>
<P>
The fog began to drift over the track shortly before midnight and quickly 
became thicker, cutting visibility to less than 100 yards. 
</P>
<P>
A caution flag came out at 1:12 a.m. because of a car stalled in a dangerous 
position in the infield. But, with the thickening fog, the pace car stayed on 
the track until officials finally decided to stop the field. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Nissan GTP, driven by 4-man team headed by Geoff Brabham, has lights on 
as it leads field as darkness falls in 24 Hours of Daytona endurance race at 
Daytona International Speedway. United Press International; Photo, (Southland 
Edition) Arie Luyendyk, right, at wheel of Nissan, leads field for start of the 
24 Hours of Daytona race. United Press International 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
