<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE BIG MIX; 
</P>
<P>
VIDEO; 
</P>
<P>
SO MANY VIDEO STORES, SO MANY LANGUAGES . . . 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By TERRY ATKINSON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It's called home video because you take it home, right? That may be generally 
true, but for hundreds of thousands of Southern Californians -- mostly 
foreign-born -- the home in home video means homeland. 
</P>
<P>
Instead of going to the Wherehouse or 20/20 or Tower, these video fans head for 
Bombay Spices or VIP Video -- or one of scores of other Los Angeles and Orange 
County shops that carry tapes from overseas. 
</P>
<P>
You want videos from Japan, Korea, Armenia, Egypt, the Philippines, Thailand, 
France or Greece? You can get 'em, if you know where to look. 
</P>
<P>
This special issue was edited by David Fox, Sunday Calendar assistant editor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Series 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES -- CULTURE; ARTS -- LOS ANGELES; VIDEO RECORDINGS; MOTION PICTURES 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA020589-0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 14692 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
February 5, 1989, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
